    <section id="scroll-one" class="frame">
        <div class="scroll-container">
            <div class="inner">
                <div class="panel">
                    <section class="cell">
                        <blockquote class="pull">Ultimately I'm interested in teaching because I think, especially in art, it can make a difference. It's a language that can convey meaning that verbal communication can't necessarily convey.</blockquote>
                        <p class="sm_name">Amie McNeil, Associate Professor, School of Art + Art History + Design</p>
                        <p>When Zirpel and McNeel asked former 3D4M students Collin Bampton and Tzyy Yi (Amy) Young to be research assistants on a big project, the two didnâ€™t know quite what they were getting into. But given the opportunity to work alongside such talented and innovative professionals, the answer was an immediate â€˜Yes.â€™</p>
                        <p>During the fabrication stage of Portfolio of Possibilities in School of Art + Art History + Designâ€™s Ceramic Metal Arts (CMA) building, Bampton and Young made molds for anvils, welded and fabricated metal parts, and weighed in on design for a couple of the key pieces that would eventually make it to MadArt.</p>
                        <p>But they werenâ€™t the only students that benefitted. Throughout early fabrication, students in classes at the CMA observed Zirpel and McNeel as both teachers and artists â€” planning, creating, failing, and starting over. They got to see first-hand what it means to be a maker. Itâ€™s not always about a clear vision for a final product. Itâ€™s about asking meaningful questions and taking bold steps to answer them.</p>
                    </section>
                </div>
